item.description:
Overview
--------

This section documents the following use cases:

* Receive jobs from Dispatch
* Job cancelations from Dispatch


Design Considerations
---------------------

Although we will not *change* the names of attributes in the payload, it is possible that we'll add *new* attributes to the payload. Therefore make sure that your payload consumption will not break if a new attribute starts being included.


Payload Structure
-----------------

Please note that the structures defined in this section are our default. If you already have your own preferred structure and/or format in which you prefer to receive updates, please let us know - there's a good chance we'll be able to accomodate you.

The [Connector Hub documentation](https://docs.dispatch.me/connector/#get-data-from-dispatch) describes the overall payload structure and how to poll for them and to send through acknowledgement. The two elements from the payload that we care about for performing the processing mentioned in this section are the `Message/Request/Type` and `Message/Request/Payload`.

To be relevant for the processing mentioned in this section, ensure that the `Type` has a value of `put_data`. If it does then extract the `Payload` which will have the following basic payload structure:

    "Payload": {
        "Actions": [
            {
                "ID": null,
                "Put": {
                    "some_event": {
                        "id": 30462
                        "external_ids": [
                            "account.999.source:enterprise_system_id"
                        ]
                        ...
                    }
                }
            }
        ]
    }



The following basics should be used for all event processing:
* `some_event` - Use this for your branch logic as described in the sections below. This can also be used to determine status.
* `external_id` - This is the Enterprise's record ID. This will appear in an array element.
* `updated_at` - Use this to mark the time the event occured in your system

request.description:
We call it a Job. You might call it a Work Order, Service Order or something else. Potato, potﾄ》o. Anyway, you will be receiving these from us. Jobs coming from the Dispatch Platform will have the following payload structure:

```
    "Payload": {
        "Actions": [
            {
                "ID": null,
                "Put": {
                    "job": {
                        "id": 30462,
                        "organization_id": 11776,
                        "title": " Claim Details 206",
                        "status": "offered",
                        "status_message": "",
                        "description": "some description",
                        "updated_at": "2018-05-18T10:05:46+0000",
                        "service_type": "air conditioning",
                        "service_fee": 0,
                        "address": {
                            "street_1": "1755 Ridgeview Dr",
                            "street_2": "",
                            "postal_code": "76012",
                            "city": "Arlington",
                            "state": "TX",
                            "country": "United States",
                            "timezone": "America/Chicago",
                            "latitude": 32.7633905735029,
                            "longitude": -97.1352367468659
                        },
                        "external_ids": [
                            "namespace:enterprise_system_id"
                        ],
                        "customer": {
                            "first_name": "James",
                            "last_name": "Dodd",
                            "company_name": "",
                            "email": "devs+dodd@dispatch.me",
                            "phone_number": "+15559803824"
                        }
                    }
                }
            }
        ]
    }
```	

It is possible and perhaps even likely that not all data will be present. The elements that are populated might vary from Enterprise to Enterprise

If an enterprise cancels a job it will come over with the following structure:

```
	"Payload": {
	    "Actions": [
	        {
	            "ID": null,
	            "Put": {
	                "job": {
	                    "id": 30462,
	                    "status": "canceled",
	                    "status_message": "",
	                    "updated_at": "2018-05-18T10:05:46+0000",
	                    "external_ids": [
	                        "namespace:enterprise_system_id"
	                    ]
	                }
	            }
	        }
	    ]
	}
```	

It is up to you to decide whether and how to handle this event (or if you want to ignore entirely let us know so we can turn off).

When you schedule an appointment send over the following:

```
    [{
		"header": {
			"record_type": "appointment",
			"version": "v3"
		},
		"record": {
			"status": "scheduled",
			"time": "2018-10-30T22:00:00.000Z",
			"duration": 14400,
			"job_id": 555
		}
	}]
```	

Where:

- `time` - this is the scheduled start window of the appointment
- `duration` - this is the duration of the appointment window in **seconds**

This is an optional but recommended update.

When you send through notes please send the following structure: 

```
	[{
		"header": {
			"record_type": "attachment",
			"version": "v3"
		},
		"record": {
			"action": "post",
			"job_id": 555,
			"description": "some note"
		}
	}]
```

Overview
========

If you wish to receive acknowledgements of transactions successfully sent to the Dispatch Platform you can subscribe to this event. By default this is not sent back into the event stream so please let us know if you want this enabled.

This event indicates acknowledgement that a transaction got processed successfully on the Dispatch side. It does not indicate that the Dispatcher acknowledged the job.

And just like any other event you'll need send an update to `agent/out` to remove this from the queue (yes you'll need to acknowledge the acknowledgement!)

Event Processing
================

These will have the following payload structure:

```
  "Payload": {
    "Actions": [{
      "ID": "34f3b843-0318-5c27-a34c-ebc4bff3e46d",
      "Put": {
        "ack": {
            "id": 555,
            "action": "inbound_ack",
            "model": "job",
            "status": 201,
            "ack_message": "Created job",
            "data": {
              "organization_id": 11789,
              "external_ids": [
                "namespace:enterprise_system_id"
              ]
            }
        }
      }
    }]
  }    
```

Where:

* `id` - the corresponding ID of the created entity in Dispatch in case you wish to store it (optional)


PLEASE NOTE that this event is only indicates if an insert/update that *you sent through* successfully happened on the Dispatch side. To this end, the very fact that you're receiving this event indicates that the transaction was successful and therefore the only thing you need to retrieve from this event is the `enterprise_system_id` in order to know which record to update on your end. Any other data contained within this event is entirely optional and most likely should be ignored.

Overview
========

If you wish to receive notification of transactions that errored out you can subscribe to this event. By default this is not sent back into the event stream so please let us know if you want this enabled. 

We attempt to only send "fixable" errors to this endpoint. That is, errors that occurred due to bad data to this endpoint. These generally tend to be errors in the 400 range.

As a general rule, the Dispatch Platform does everything to avoid transactions being rejected. As long as the minimal amout of data for a transaction is available the transaction will succeed. As such, we believe that errors are likely to occur during the testing phase of the project and thereafter should be very few and far between.

Event Processing
================

These will have the following payload structure:

```
	"Payload": {
	    "Actions": [
	        {
	            "ID": "167e4f3e-b644-5031-9946-1cbcecefff44",
	            "Put": {
	                "err": {
	                    "payload": {
	                        "data_type": "customer",
	                        "details": {
	                            "response": "{\"errors\":{\"phone_numbers\":[\"contain invalid phone number '+1901486247'\"]}}",
	                            "code": 422,
	                            "method": "POST"
	                        },
	                        "data": {
	                            "external_ids": [
	                                "0083702"
	                            ],
	                            "first_name": "Mike",
	                            "last_name": "Smith",
	                            "notes": "Discount: 0.0\nLateCharge: 1.5",
	                            "billing_address": {
	                                "street_1": "1001 Donnegan Cv",
	                                "city": "Minneaplois",
	                                "state": "MN",
	                                "postal_code": "55408"
	                            },
	                            "phone_number": "+1555486247",
	                            "organization_id": 11789
	                        }
	                    }
	                }
	            }
	        }
	    ]
	}
```

Where:

* `data_type` - the record type for which the error occurred
* `details` - error details
* `data` - the payload with the offending data
